\section{Model development}

\subsection{Perceptual model}

Our understanding of farming practices and decision making in northern India was informed by more than 200 semi-structured interviews carried out by the first author in four districts of Uttar Pradesh, a large and diverse state in northern India. The interviews sought to obtain information on irrigation water use, agricultural practices and constraints as well as socio-economic and environmental factors influencing rural livelihoods. A complete description of the methodology and results of the field campaign are provided in \citet{okeeffe_use_2015}. Our perceptual model of agricultural water use in Uttar Pradesh is based around the following key observations:

% TODO: include more information here

\begin{itemize}
\item \noindent \textit{Conjunctive use of water sources}\\
Irrigation canals provide an irregular but important source of water to some farmers and because of the low cost are used in preference to groundwater when possible. Proximity to a canal is not always an indication of access.

\item \noindent \textit{Irrigation scheduling}\\
Farmers typically follow a set irrigation schedule. However, as access to or availability of water can be an issue, farmers may not always irrigate at the optimum time.

\item \noindent \textit{Farmers will continue to irrigate despite increasing prices}\\
While the price of irrigation was found to be a major concern for farmers, it did not have a significant influence on irrigation practices.

\item \noindent \textit{Canal recharge}\\ 
Farmers with land located close to a working canal may benefit from canal leakage, with additional aquifer recharge, leading to more stable groundwater levels and lower pumping costs.

\item \noindent \textit{Water application is not measured}\\
Farmers do not record the volume of water they apply to crops, instead observing the approximate depth water reaches within their fields (e.g. approximately 10 cm) \citep{OKeeffe2016}. 

\item \noindent \textit{Irrigation return flow}\\
The majority of farmers use flood irrigation, much of which is lost through evaporation or returned to the underlying aquifer.

\item \noindent \textit{Irrigation time increases with decreasing water tables}\\
Farmers described increasing irrigation costs with decreasing groundwater levels, particularly during the dry, pre-monsoon season.

\item \noindent \textit{Farmers' solution to lack of water: drill deeper wells}\\
The most common solution to declining water tables reported by farmers was to drill deeper wells. 
\end{itemize}

A graphical representation of these observations is shown in Figure~\ref{fig:DecisionFlow}. The perceptual model was conceptualized using a series of rules governing the way in which irrigators behave under various situations and how they are most likely to act when their circumstances change... three coupled submodels representing hydrology, crop yield and farmer livelihood. \\

\subsection{Hydrology}

A single cell model simulates the response of water resources to changing socioeconomic and environmental conditions. This class of hydrological model is commonly used in the field of water resources economics and there is an extensive body of literature describing their application \citep[see][]{DeFrutosCachorro2014, Gisser1973, Koundouri2004a}. The aquifer is represented as a ``bath-tub'' with spatially homogeneous hydrogeological characteristics, including groundwater level. Changes in groundwater level, based on irrigation water demand, water source and its availability, rainfall and irrigation method, are instantaneously applied across the entire cell. \\

\subsubsection{Root zone}
The soil column is represented in terms of the \textit{total available water}, TAW, which describes the maximum amount of water that is available to plants at field capacity:

\begin{equation}
TAW = (\theta_{FC} - \theta_{WP})Z_{r,c}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\theta_{FC}$ and $\theta_{WP}$ are respectively the field capacity and wilting point and $Z_{r}$ is the maximum root depth of the overlying crop, $c$. The proportion of TAW that can easily be extracted from the root zone before the soil moisture deficit impedes plant growth is termed the \textit{readily available water},

\begin{equation}
RAW = (1-p_{c})TAW
\end{equation}

\noindent where $p_{c}$ is the crop-specific depletion factor. \\

The daily water balance equation expressed in terms of root zone depletion, $D_{r}$, is written

\begin{equation}
\frac{dD_{r}}{dt} = ET_{c,t} + R_{t} - (P_{t}-RO_{t}) - I_{t}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $ET_{c,t}$ is actual crop evapotranspiration, $R_{t}$ is recharge, $P$ is precipitation, $RO$ is surface runoff and $I_{t}$ is irrigation. Crop evapotranspiration is determined as follows:

\begin{equation}
ET_{c} = K_{s}K_{c}ET_{0}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $K_{c}$ is a crop coefficient which varies according to the crop growth, $K_{s}$ is a water stress coefficient and $ET_{0}$ is reference evapotranspiration. We use the Hargreaves-Samani equation to estimate $ET_{0}$, as follows:

\begin{equation}
ET_{0} = 0.0135 \times 0.17 \times (T_{mean} + 17.8) \times (T_{max} - T_{min})^{0.5}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $T_{mean}$, $T_{max}$ and $T_{min}$ are daily mean, maximum and minimum temperature, respectively. Crop coefficients are obtained from the FAO (TODO: provide reference). The water stress coefficient is calculated:

\begin{equation}
K_{s} = \frac{TAW-D_{r}}{(1-p)TAW}.
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Groundwater}

Recharge, $R_{t}$ from the root zone to the underlying aquifer is assumed to occur when the water content of the root zone exceeds field capacity:

\begin{equation}
  R_{t}=
    \begin{cases}
      -D_{r}, & \text{if}\ D_{r} < 0\\
      0, & \text{otherwise}.
    \end{cases}
\end{equation}

