\subsection{Crop yield}

Crop yield is an important link between farmer livelihood and agricultural water use. It is calculated using the relationship between crop production and evapotranspiration developed by \citet{Doorenbos1979a}, written as

\begin{equation}
\left(1-\frac{Y_{a}}{Y_{x}}\right) = K_{y}\left(1-\frac{ET_{c}}{ET_{x}}\right)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $Y_{x}$ is maximum yield, $Y_{a}$ is actual yield, $K_{y}$ is the yield response factor, $ET_{x}$ is maximum evapotranspiration and $ET_{c}$ is actual crop evapotranspiration. While there are other constraints on crop production, including labour and nutrient availability, farmers in the four districts... stated that water availability was the largest constraint on production. \\

\subsection{Livelihood}

Fundamental to the model is its conceptualization of the feedbacks which exist between farmer livelihood and irrigation behaviour. Farmer livelihood, $L$, at time $t$ is considered in terms of the difference between farm income, $m$, and farm expenditure, $z$, as follows:

\begin{equation}
L_{t} = m_{t} - z_{t}.
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Income}

\noindent Income is the amount of money a farmer receives at market for their crop, expressed

\begin{equation}
m(t) = \sum_{c=1}^{n} y_{c} q_{c} A_{c}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $n$ is number of crops grown in an agricultural year and $y_{c}$, $q_{c}$ and $A_{c}$ are yield, price and Area of crop $c$. Crop price data is retrieved from national statistics [TODO: provide reference], and farm area is fixed at one hectare based on information collected in the field. \\

